{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502109"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:39:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:39:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1826"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.07,0.23,0.01,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1826"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93462"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45269"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man weighing 80 kg is admitted to hospital following a laparoscopic repair of an incarcerated para-oesophageal hernia. The procedure was uncomplicated. Twelve hours post-operatively, he reports feeling well. He has no significant past medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well and is sitting up in bed. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with mild port-site tenderness. His urine output since the operation has been 100 mL. He has intravenous isotonic saline running at 80 mL/hour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal sodium 140 mmol/L (135-145), potassium 5.3 mmol/L (3.5-5.5), and creatinine 95 \u03bcmol/L (60-110).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current fluid regimen","Intravenous furosemide","One litre Hartmann\u0027s solution bolus","Intravenous ephedrine","One litre isotonic saline over four hours"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-operative oliguria (urine output \u0026lt;0.5 mL/kg/hour) and relative hypotension, suggesting hypovolaemia. With a weight of 80 kg, his expected minimum urine output should be 40 mL/hour (0.5 mL/kg/hour \u00d7 80 kg). His actual urine output of 100 mL over 12 hours (approximately eight mL/hour) indicates inadequate renal perfusion. His current fluid replacement of 80 mL/hour has been insufficient to maintain adequate intravascular volume following surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne litre isotonic saline over four hours\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This will provide volume resuscitation at a rate of 250 mL/hour, which should improve his blood pressure and renal perfusion without causing fluid overload. Isotonic saline is preferred as his potassium is already at 5.3 mmol/L, near the upper limit of normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current fluid regimen\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the current rate has clearly been insufficient to maintain adequate urine output and blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this hypovolaemic patient. Diuretics would worsen his volume depletion and could precipitate acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne litre Hartmann\u0027s solution bolus\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided because Hartmann\u0027s solution contains 5 mmol/L of potassium. With his potassium already at 5.3 mmol/L, additional potassium could precipitate hyperkalaemia. Additionally, a rapid bolus may be excessive for this stable patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ephedrine\u003C/strong\u003E is used for acute intraoperative hypotension during anaesthesia. At 12 hours post-operatively, the anaesthetic effects have worn off, and his hypotension is due to hypovolaemia rather than vasodilation. Vasopressors without addressing the underlying volume deficit would be inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-operative hypotension is often due to inadequate fluid replacement."],"references":["Siparsky N. Overview of postoperative fluid therapy in adults [Internet]. UpToDate. 2020. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-postoperative-fluid-therapy-in-adults","Lonjaret L, Lairez O, Geeraerts T, Minville V. Optimal perioperative management of arterial blood pressure. Integrated Blood Pressure Control. 2014;:49."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93462"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93462"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T19:31:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T19:33:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1826"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111334"}}},"meta":